# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: can-bus-automotive
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] These standards are specified in Clauses 125 and 126 of the IEEE 802.3 standard.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The physical (PHY) layer transmission technology of IEEE 802.3bz is based on 10GBASE-T, but operates at a lower signaling rate.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] By reducing the original signal rate to 1⁄4 or 1⁄2, the link speed drops to 2.5 or 5 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The spectral bandwidth of the signal is reduced accordingly, lowering the requirements on the cabling, so that 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T can be deployed at a cable length of up to 100 m on Cat 5e or better cables.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The NBASE-T effort also standardized how its switches can implement power over Ethernet according to the IEEE 802.3at and successor standards.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] This allows a single cable to provide both power and data for high-bandwidth wireless access points such as those that implement the IEEE 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) and IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) standards.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] Prior to the release of 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T, manufacturers of wireless access points that wanted to support multi-gigabit uplink speed using standard gigabit Ethernet ports had to include multiple Ethernet ports on their access points.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] By bonding the connections from multiple Ethernet ports via IEEE 802.3ad link aggregation or similar, manufacturers were able to achieve speeds close to 2 Gbit/s by using two ports that support gigabit speeds.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] This would require the wireless access point to be connected to the rest of the network with 2 Ethernet cables and require both the wireless access point and network hardware to support and be configured for link aggregation.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] Wireless access points that support 2.5GBASE-T or 5GBASE-T eliminate this complexity.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] In 2013 with the release of IEEE 802.11ac (Wi-Fi 5), wireless access points for the first time could reach speeds of 2 Gbit/s or 4 Gbit/s, exceeding the 1 Gbit/s IEEE 802.3ab 1000BASE-T wired Ethernet uplink.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] While 10GBASE-T had already been standardized since 2006, this standard used a higher signaling frequency that would have substantially limited the maximum distance of Cat5e cable runs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] Therefore, there was demand for an intermediate standard that could uplink the 2 Gbit/s and 4 Gbit/s speeds from wireless access points over existing Cat5e cable.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The development of the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards enabled wireless access points to reach their maximum speeds without being limited by the Ethernet uplink speeds over a single existing Cat5e cable, while also being compatible with newer Cat6 and Cat6a cabling.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards also serve as an interim solution for achieving lower-cost and lower power consumption multi-gigabit network speeds.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] As of Dec 2022, 10GBASE-T network equipment is still substantially more expensive than 1GBASE-T, 2.5GBASE-T, and 5GBASE-T network equipment.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3bz also supports power over Ethernet, which had previously not been available with IEEE 802.3an 10GBASE-T.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] As early as 2013, the Intel Avoton server processors integrated 2.5 Gbit/s Ethernet ports.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] Whilst Broadcom had announced a series of 2.5 Gbit/s transceiver ICs, 2.5 Gbit/s switch hardware was not widely commercially available at that point.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] Many early 10GBASE-T switches, particularly those with SFP+ interfaces, do not support the intermediate speeds.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] In October 2014, the NBASE-T Alliance was founded, initially comprising Cisco, Aquantia, Freescale, and Xilinx.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] By December 2015, it contained more than 45 companies, and aimed to have its specification compatible with 802.3bz.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The competing MGBASE-T Alliance, stating the same faster Gigabit Ethernet objectives, was founded in December 2014.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] In contrast to NBASE-T, the MGBASE-T said that their specifications would be open source.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3's 2.5G/5GBASE-T Task Force started working on the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards in March 2015.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The two NBASE-T and MGBASE-T Alliances ended up collaborating. with the forming of the IEEE 802.3bz Task Force under the patronage of the Ethernet Alliance in June 2015.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] On September 23, 2016, the IEEE-SA Standards Board approved IEEE Std 802.3bz-2016.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] The IEEE 802.3ch-2020 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 standards are derived from the IEEE 802.3bp-2016 1000BASE-T1 Ethernet over single twisted pair standard, and share very little in common with the similarly named 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards at the PHY layer.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 can run over a single twisted pair up to 15 meters in length, use PAM8 modulation (compared to PAM3 modulation in 1000BASE-T1 or PAM-16 + 128DSQ in 2.5GBASE-T/5GBASE-T), and are standardized in 802.3ch-2020.
[src:can-bus-automotive/automotive-ethernet] Their primary use is in embedded automotive applications, and are commonly referred to as part of the Automotive Ethernet family of standards, along with 100BASE-T1 and 1000BASE-T1.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A **controller area network** (**CAN**) is a vehicle bus standard designed to enable efficient communication primarily between electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Originally developed to reduce the complexity and cost of electrical wiring in automobiles through multiplexing, the CAN bus protocol has since been adopted in various other contexts, such as 3D printing.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This broadcast-based, message-oriented protocol ensures data integrity and prioritization through a process called arbitration, allowing the highest priority device to continue transmitting if multiple devices attempt to send data simultaneously, while others back off.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Its reliability is enhanced by differential signaling, which mitigates electrical noise.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If one side of the differential signal is lost, the system can switch to one wire communication.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This is to ensure data communication for critical systems.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Common versions of the CAN protocol include CAN 2.0, CAN FD, and CAN XL which vary in their data rate capabilities and maximum data payload sizes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Development of the CAN bus started in 1983 at Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The protocol was officially released in 1986 at the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) conference in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The first CAN controller chips were introduced by Intel in 1987, and shortly thereafter by Philips.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Released in 1991, the Mercedes-Benz W140 was the first production vehicle to feature a CAN-based multiplex wiring system.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Bosch published several versions of the CAN specification.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The latest is CAN 2.0, published in 1991.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Part A is for the standard format with an 11-bit identifier, and part B is for the extended format with a 29-bit identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A CAN device that uses 11-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0A, and a CAN device that uses 29-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0B.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] These standards are freely available from Bosch along with other specifications and white papers.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In 1993, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) released CAN standard ISO 11898, which was later restructured into two parts: ISO 11898-1 which covers the data link layer, and ISO 11898-2 which covers the CAN physical layer for high-speed CAN.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-3 was released later and covers the CAN physical layer for low-speed, fault-tolerant CAN.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The physical layer standards ISO 11898-2 and ISO 11898-3 are not part of the Bosch CAN 2.0 specification.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In 2012, Bosch released CAN FD 1.0, or CAN with Flexible Data-Rate.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This specification uses a different frame format that allows a different data length as well as optionally switching to a faster bit rate after the arbitration is decided.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN FD is compatible with existing CAN 2.0 networks so new CAN FD devices can coexist on the same network with existing CAN devices, using the same CAN 2.0 communication parameters.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] As of 2018, Bosch was active in extending CAN standards.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The CAN bus is one of five protocols used in the on-board diagnostics (OBD)-II vehicle diagnostics standard.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The OBD-II standard has been mandatory for all cars and light trucks sold in the United States since model year 1996.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The EOBD standard has been mandatory for all petrol vehicles sold in the European Union since 2001 and all diesel vehicles since 2004.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The modern automobile may have as many as 70 electronic control units (ECUs) for various subsystems.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Usually the biggest processor is the engine control unit.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Others are used for autonomous driving, advanced driver assistance system (ADAS), transmission, airbags, antilock braking/ABS, cruise control, electric power steering, audio systems, power windows, doors, mirror adjustment, battery and recharging systems for hybrid/electric cars, etc.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Some of these form independent subsystems, but communication among others is essential.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A subsystem may need to control actuators or receive feedback from sensors.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard was devised to fill this need.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In recent years, the LIN bus (Local Interconnect Network) standard has been introduced to complement CAN for non-critical subsystems such as air-conditioning and infotainment, where data transmission speed and reliability are less critical.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN bus is often used to connect 3D printer mainboards to expansion boards due to its high electrical noise tolerance, especially from ground noise generated by stepper motors, commonly used in 3D printers and other CNC applications.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The CAN FD variant is used by many, such as the Duet3D controller family, as it has higher bandwidth needed to support the high command rates of 3D printing.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Due to its legacy, CAN 2.0 is the most widely used protocol with a maximum payload size of eight bytes and a typical baud rate of 500 kbit/s.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Classical CAN, which includes CAN 2.0A (Standard CAN) and CAN 2.0B (Extended CAN), primarily differs in identifier field lengths: CAN 2.0A uses an 11-bit identifier, while CAN 2.0B employs a 29-bit identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The longer identifier in CAN 2.0B allows for a greater number of unique message identifiers, which is beneficial in complex systems with many nodes and data types.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] However, this increase in unique message identifiers also increases frame length, which in turn reduces the maximum data rate.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Additionally, the extended identifier provides finer control over message prioritization due to more available identifier values.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This, however, may introduce compatibility issues; CAN 2.0A devices can generally communicate with CAN 2.0B devices, but not vice versa, due to potential errors in handling longer identifiers.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 1 Mbit/s and is the basis for higher-layer protocols.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In contrast, low-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 125 kbit/s and offers fault tolerance by allowing communication to continue despite a fault in one of the two wires, with each node maintaining its own termination.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN FD (Flexible Data-Rate), standardized as ISO 11898-1, was developed by Bosch and released in 2012 to meet the need for increased data transfer in modern high-performance vehicles.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN FD also introduces a flexible data field size, increasing the maximum size from 8 bytes to 64 bytes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This flexibility allows for more efficient data transmission by reducing the number of frames needed for large data transfers, which is beneficial for applications like high-resolution sensor data or software updates.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN FD maintains backward compatibility with CAN 2.0 devices by using the same frame format as CAN 2.0B, with the addition of a new control field to indicate whether the frame is a CAN FD frame or a standard CAN 2.0 frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This allows CAN FD devices to coexist with CAN 2.0 devices on the same bus, while higher data rates and larger data payloads are available only when communicating with other CAN FD devices.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN XL, specified by CiA 610-1 and standardized as part of ISO11898-1, supports up to 2,048-byte payloads and data rates up to 20 Mbit/s.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] It bridges the gap between CAN FD and Ethernet (100BASE-T1) while maintaining CAN's collision-resolution benefits.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN XL controllers can also handle Classical CAN and CAN FD communication, ensuring compatibility in mixed networks.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Its large data fields allow for higher layer protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) and the tunneling of Ethernet frames.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Most of the CAN standard applies to the transfer layer.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer receives messages from the physical layer and transmits those messages to the object layer.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer is responsible for bit timing and synchronization, message framing, arbitration, acknowledgment, error detection and signaling, and fault confinement.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN bus (ISO 11898-1:2003) originally specified the link layer protocol with only abstract requirements for the physical layer, e.g., asserting the use of a medium with multiple-access at the bit level through the use of dominant and recessive states.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The electrical aspects of the physical layer (voltage, current, number of conductors) were specified in ISO 11898-2:2003, which is now widely accepted.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] However, the mechanical aspects of the physical layer (connector type and number, colors, labels, pin-outs) have yet to be formally specified.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] As a result, an automotive ECU will typically have a particular—often custom—connector with various sorts of cables, of which two are the CAN bus lines.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This *de facto* mechanical standard for CAN could be implemented with the node having both male and female 9-pin D-sub connectors electrically wired to each other in parallel within the node.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Bus power is fed to a node's male connector and the bus draws power from the node's female connector.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This follows the electrical engineering convention that power sources are terminated at female connectors.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Adoption of this standard avoids the need to fabricate custom splitters to connect two sets of bus wires to a single D connector at each node.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Such nonstandard (custom) wire harnesses (splitters) that join conductors outside the node reduce bus reliability, eliminate cable interchangeability, reduce compatibility of wiring harnesses, and increase cost.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The absence of a complete physical layer specification (mechanical in addition to electrical) freed the CAN bus specification from the constraints and complexity of physical implementation.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] However, it left CAN bus implementations open to interoperability issues due to mechanical incompatibility.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In order to improve interoperability, many vehicle makers have generated specifications describing a set of allowed CAN transceivers in combination with requirements on the parasitic capacitance on the line.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The allowed parasitic capacitance includes both capacitors as well as ESD protection (ESD against ISO 7637-3).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In addition to parasitic capacitance, 12V and 24V systems do not have the same requirements in terms of line maximum voltage.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Indeed, during jump start events light vehicle lines can go up to 24V while truck systems can go as high as 36V.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] New solutions are emerging, allowing the same component to be used for CAN as well as CAN FD (see ).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Noise immunity on ISO 11898-2:2003 is achieved by maintaining the differential impedance of the bus at a low level with low-value resistors (120 ohms) at each end of the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] However, when dormant, a low-impedance bus such as CAN draws more current (and power) than other voltage-based signaling buses.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] On CAN bus systems, balanced line operation, where current in one signal line is exactly balanced by current in the opposite direction in the other signal provides an independent, stable 0 V reference for the receivers.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Best practice determines that CAN bus balanced pair signals be carried in twisted pair wires in a shielded cable to minimize RF emission and reduce interference susceptibility in the already noisy RF environment of an automobile.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 provides some immunity to common mode voltage between transmitter and receiver by having a 0 V rail running along the bus to maintain a high degree of voltage association between the nodes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Also, in the de facto mechanical configuration mentioned above, a supply rail is included to distribute power to each of the transceiver nodes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The design provides a common supply for all the transceivers.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The actual voltage to be applied by the bus and which nodes apply to it are application-specific and not formally specified.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Common practice node design provides each node with transceivers that are optically isolated from their node host and derive a 5 V linearly regulated supply voltage for the transceivers from the universal supply rail provided by the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This usually allows operating margin on the supply rail sufficient to allow interoperability across many node types.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Typical values of supply voltage on such networks are 7 to 30 V.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] However, the lack of a formal standard means that system designers are responsible for supply rail compatibility.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 describes the electrical implementation formed from a multi-dropped single-ended balanced line configuration with resistor termination at each end of the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In this configuration a dominant state is asserted by one or more transmitters switching the CAN− to supply 0 V and (simultaneously) switching CAN+ to the +5 V bus voltage thereby forming a current path through the resistors that terminate the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] As such the terminating resistors form an essential component of the signaling system, and are included, not just to limit wave reflection at high frequency.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] During a recessive state, the signal lines and resistor(s) remain in a high-impedance state with respect to both rails.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Voltages on both CAN+ and CAN− tend (weakly) towards a voltage midway between the rails.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A recessive state is present on the bus only when none of the transmitters on the bus is asserting a dominant state.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] During a dominant state, the signal lines and resistor(s) move to a low-impedance state with respect to the rails so that current flows through the resistor.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN+ voltage tends to +5 V and CAN− tends to 0 V.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Irrespective of signal state the signal lines are always in a low-impedance state with respect to one another by virtue of the terminating resistors at the end of the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This signaling strategy differs significantly from other balanced line transmission technologies such as RS-422/3, RS-485, etc. which employ differential line drivers/ receivers and use a signaling system based on the differential mode voltage of the balanced line crossing a notional 0 V.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on such systems normally relies on the media supporting three states (active high, active low and inactive tri-state) and is dealt with in the time domain.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on CAN bus is achieved by the electrical logic of the system supporting just two states that are conceptually analogous to a ‘wired AND’ network.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN is a multi-master serial bus standard for connecting electronic control units (ECUs) also known as nodes (automotive electronics is a major application domain).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Two or more nodes are required on the CAN bus to communicate.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A node may interface to devices from simple digital logic e.g.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] PLD, via FPGA up to an embedded computer running extensive software.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Such a computer may also be a gateway allowing a general-purpose computer (like a laptop) to communicate over a USB or Ethernet port to the devices on a CAN bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] All nodes are connected to each other through a physically conventional *two-wire bus*.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The wires are a twisted pair with a 120 Ω (nominal) characteristic impedance.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This bus uses differential wired-AND signals.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Two signals, CAN high (CANH) and CAN low (CANL) are either driven to a "dominant" state with CANH > CANL, or not driven and pulled by passive resistors to a "recessive" state with CANH ≤ CANL.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A 0 data bit encodes a dominant state, while a 1 data bit encodes a recessive state, supporting a wired-AND convention, which gives nodes with lower ID numbers priority on the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] (Receivers consider any differential voltage of less than 0.5 V to be recessive.) The dominant differential voltage is a nominal 2 V.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The dominant common mode voltage (CANH+CANL)/2 must be within 1.5 to 3.5 V of common, while the recessive common mode voltage must be within ±12 of common.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN signaling operates similarly to high-speed CAN, but with larger voltage swings.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The dominant state is transmitted by driving CANH towards the device power supply voltage (5 V or 3.3 V), and CANL towards 0 V when transmitting a dominant (0), while the termination resistors pull the bus to a recessive state with CANH at 0 V and CANL at 5 V.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This allows a simpler receiver that just considers the sign of CANH−CANL.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Both wires must be able to handle −27 to +40 V without damage.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] With both high-speed and low-speed CAN, the speed of the transition is faster when a recessive-to-dominant transition occurs since the CAN wires are being actively driven.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The speed of the dominant-to-recessive transition depends primarily on the length of the CAN network and the capacitance of the wire used.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN is usually used in automotive and industrial applications where the bus runs from one end of the environment to the other.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Fault-tolerant CAN is often used where groups of nodes need to be connected together.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The specifications require the bus be kept within a minimum and maximum common mode bus voltage but do not define how to keep the bus within this range.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The termination resistors are needed to suppress reflections as well as return the bus to its recessive or idle state.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN uses a 120 Ω resistor at each end of a linear bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Low-speed CAN uses resistors at each node.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Other types of terminations may be used such as the Terminating Bias Circuit defined in ISO11783.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A terminating bias circuit provides power and ground in addition to the CAN signaling on a four-wire cable.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This provides automatic electrical bias and termination at each end of each bus segment.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] An ISO11783 network is designed for hot plug-in and removal of bus segments and ECUs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Each node is able to send and receive messages, but not simultaneously.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A message or Frame consists primarily of the ID (identifier), which represents the priority of the message, and up to eight data bytes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A CRC, acknowledge slot [ACK] and other overhead are also part of the message.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD extends the length of the data section to up to 64 bytes per frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The message is transmitted serially onto the bus using a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) format and may be received by all nodes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The devices that are connected by a CAN network are typically sensors, actuators, and other control devices.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] These devices are connected to the bus through a host processor, a CAN controller, and a CAN transceiver.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN data transmission uses a lossless bitwise arbitration method of contention resolution.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This arbitration method requires all nodes on the CAN network to be synchronized to sample every bit on the CAN network at the same time.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Unfortunately the term synchronous is imprecise since the data is transmitted in an asynchronous format, namely without a clock signal.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The CAN specifications use the terms *dominant* bits and *recessive* bits, where dominant is a logical 0 (actively driven to a voltage by the transmitter) and recessive is a logical 1 (passively returned to a voltage by a resistor).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The idle state is represented by the recessive level (Logical 1).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If one node transmits a dominant bit and another node transmits a recessive bit then there is a collision and the dominant bit wins.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This means there is no delay to the higher-priority message, and the node transmitting the lower-priority message automatically attempts to re-transmit six-bit clocks after the end of the dominant message.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This makes CAN very suitable as a real-time prioritized communications system.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The exact voltages for a logical 0 or 1 depend on the physical layer used, but the basic principle of CAN requires that each node listen to the data on the CAN network including the transmitting node(s) itself (themselves).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If a logical 1 is transmitted by all transmitting nodes at the same time, then a logical 1 is seen by all of the nodes, including both the transmitting node(s) and receiving node(s).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is transmitted by all transmitting node(s) at the same time, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, and a logical 1 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes including the node(s) transmitting the logical 1.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] When a node transmits a logical 1 but sees a logical 0, it realizes that there is a contention and it quits transmitting.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] By using this process, any node that transmits a logical 1, when another node transmits a logical 0, loses the arbitration and drops out.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A node that loses arbitration re-queues its message for later transmission and the CAN frame bit-stream continues without error until only one node is left transmitting.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This means that the node that transmits the first 1 loses arbitration.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Since the 11 bit (or 29bit for CAN 2.0B) identifier is transmitted by all nodes at the start of the CAN frame, the node with the lowest identifier transmits more zeros at the start of the frame, and that is the node that wins the arbitration or has the highest priority.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] For example, consider an 11-bit ID CAN network, with two nodes with IDs of 15 (binary representation, 00000001111) and 16 (binary representation, 00000010000).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If these two nodes transmit at the same time, each will first transmit the start bit then transmit the first six zeros of their ID with no arbitration decision being made.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] When ID bit 4 is transmitted, the node with the ID of 16 transmits a 1 (recessive) for its ID, and the node with the ID of 15 transmits a 0 (dominant) for its ID.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] When this happens, the node with the ID of 16 knows it transmitted a 1, but sees a 0 and realizes that there is a collision and it lost arbitration.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Node 16 stops transmitting which allows the node with ID of 15 to continue its transmission without any loss of data.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The node with the lowest ID will always win the arbitration and therefore has the highest priority.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Bit rates up to 1 Mbit/s are possible at network lengths below 40 m.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Decreasing the bit rate allows longer network distances (e.g.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD standard allows increasing the bit rate after arbitration and can increase the speed of the data section by a factor of up to ten or more of the arbitration bit rate.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] All nodes on the CAN network must operate at the same nominal bit rate, but noise, phase shifts, oscillator tolerance and oscillator drift mean that the actual bit rate might not be the nominal bit rate.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Since a separate clock signal is not used, a means of synchronizing the nodes is necessary.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is important during arbitration since the nodes in arbitration must be able to see both their transmitted data and the other nodes' transmitted data at the same time.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is also important to ensure that variations in oscillator timing between nodes do not cause errors.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Synchronization starts with a hard synchronization on the first recessive to dominant transition after a period of bus idle (the start bit).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Resynchronization occurs on every recessive to dominant transition during the frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The CAN controller expects the transition to occur at a multiple of the nominal bit time.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If the transition does not occur at the exact time the controller expects it, the controller adjusts the nominal bit time accordingly.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The adjustment is accomplished by dividing each bit into a number of time slices called quanta, and assigning some number of quanta to each of the four segments within the bit: synchronization, propagation, phase segment 1 and phase segment 2.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The number of quanta the bit is divided into can vary by controller, and the number of quanta assigned to each segment can be varied depending on bit rate and network conditions.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A transition that occurs before or after it is expected causes the controller to calculate the time difference and lengthen phase segment 1 or shorten phase segment 2 by this time.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This effectively adjusts the timing of the receiver to the transmitter to synchronize them.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This resynchronization process is done continuously at every recessive to dominant transition to ensure the transmitter and receiver stay in sync.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Continuously resynchronizing reduces errors induced by noise, and allows a receiving node that was synchronized to a node that lost arbitration to resynchronize to the node which won arbitration.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Message IDs must be unique on a single CAN bus, otherwise two nodes would continue transmission beyond the end of the arbitration field (ID) causing an error.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In the early 1990s, the choice of IDs for messages was done simply on the basis of identifying the type of data and the sending node; however, as the ID is also used as the message priority, this led to poor real-time performance.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In those scenarios, a low CAN bus use of around 30% was commonly required to ensure that all messages would meet their deadlines.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] However, if IDs are instead determined based on the deadline of the message, the lower the numerical ID and hence the higher the message priority, then bus use of 70 to 80% can typically be achieved before any message deadlines are missed.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Data frames and remote frames are separated from preceding frames by a bit field called interframe space.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Interframe space consists of at least three consecutive recessive (1) bits.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Following that, if a dominant bit is detected, it will be regarded as the *Start of frame* bit of the next frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Overload frames and error frames are not preceded by an interframe space and multiple overload frames are not separated by an interframe space.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Interframe space contains the bit fields intermission and bus idle, and suspend transmission for error passive stations, which have been transmitter of the previous message.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A CAN network can be configured to work with two different message (or *frame*) formats: the standard or base frame format (described in CAN 2.0 A and CAN 2.0 B), and the extended frame format (described only by CAN 2.0 B).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The only difference between the two formats is that the *CAN base frame* supports a length of 11 bits for the identifier, and the *CAN extended frame* supports a length of 29 bits for the identifier, made up of the 11-bit identifier (base identifier) and an 18-bit extension (identifier extension).
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The distinction between CAN base frame format and CAN extended frame format is made by using the IDE bit, which is transmitted as dominant in case of an 11-bit frame, and transmitted as recessive in case of a 29-bit frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] CAN controllers that support extended frame format messages are also able to send and receive messages in CAN base frame format.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] All frames begin with a start-of-frame (SOF) bit that denotes the start of the frame transmission.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The data frame is the only frame for actual data transmission.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard requires that the implementation must accept the base frame format and may accept the extended frame format, but must tolerate the extended frame format.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The frame format is as follows: The bit values are described for CAN-LO signal.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The two identifier fields (A & B) combine to form a 29-bit identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In the event of a data frame and a remote frame with the same identifier being transmitted at the same time, the data frame wins arbitration due to the dominant RTR bit following the identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The overload frame contains the two bit fields: Overload Flag and Overload Delimiter.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Detection of a dominant bit during intermission.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The start of an overload frame due to case 1 is only allowed to be started at the first bit time of an expected intermission, whereas overload frames due to case 2 start one bit after detecting the dominant bit.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Overload Flag consists of six dominant bits.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The overall form corresponds to that of the active error flag.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The overload flag's form destroys the fixed form of the intermission field.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] As a consequence, all other stations also detect an overload condition and on their part start transmission of an overload flag.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Overload Delimiter consists of eight recessive bits.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The overload delimiter is of the same form as the error delimiter.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The acknowledge slot is used to acknowledge the receipt of a valid CAN frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Each node that receives the frame, without finding an error, transmits a dominant level in the ACK slot and thus overrides the recessive level of the transmitter.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] If a transmitter detects a recessive level in the ACK slot, it knows that no receiver found a valid frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] A receiving node may transmit a recessive to indicate that it did not receive a valid frame, but another node that did receive a valid frame may override this with a dominant.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The transmitting node cannot know that the message has been received by all of the nodes on the CAN network.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Often, the mode of operation of the device is to re-transmit unacknowledged frames over and over.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This may lead to eventually entering the *error passive* state.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] To ensure enough transitions to maintain synchronization, a bit of opposite polarity is inserted after five consecutive bits of the same polarity.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This practice is called bit stuffing, and is necessary due to the non-return-to-zero (NRZ) coding used with CAN.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The stuffed data frames are destuffed by the receiver.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] All fields in the frame are stuffed with the exception of the CRC delimiter, ACK field and end of frame which are a fixed size and are not stuffed.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] In the fields where bit stuffing is used, six consecutive bits of the same polarity (111111 or 000000) are considered an error.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] An active error flag can be transmitted by a node when an error has been detected.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The active error flag consists of six consecutive dominant bits and violates the rule of bit stuffing.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Bit stuffing means that data frames may be larger than one would expect by simply enumerating the bits shown in the tables above.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] The stuffing bit itself may be the first of the five consecutive identical bits, so in the worst case there is one stuffing bit per four original bits.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] where n is the number of data bytes, a maximum of 8.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] Since $8n+44$ is the size of the frame before stuffing, in the worst case one bit will be added every four original bits after the first one (hence the −1 at the numerator) and, because of the layout of the bits of the header, only 34 out of 44 of them can be subject to bit stuffing.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] An undesirable side effect of the bit stuffing scheme is that a small number of bit errors in a received message may corrupt the destuffing process, causing a larger number of errors to propagate through the destuffed message.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This reduces the level of protection that would otherwise be offered by the CRC against the original errors.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p01] This deficiency of the protocol has been addressed in CAN FD frames by the use of a combination of fixed stuff bits and a counter that records the number of stuff bits inserted.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] As the CAN standard does not include common communication features, such as flow control, device addressing, and transportation of data blocks larger than one message, and above all, application data, many implementations of higher layer protocols were created.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Several are standardized for a business area, although all can be extended by each manufacturer.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] For passenger cars, each manufacturer has its own standard.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] CAN in Automation (CiA) is the international users' and manufacturers' organization that develops and supports CAN-based higher-layer protocols and their international standardization.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] The CANopen Special Interest Group (SIG) "Lift Control", which was founded in 2001, develops the CANopen application profile CiA 417 for lift control systems.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] It works on extending the features, improves technical content and ensures that the current legal standards for lift control systems are met.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] The first version of CiA 417 was published (available for CiA members) in summer 2003, version 2.0 in February 2010, version 2.1.0 in July 2012, version 2.2.0 in December 2015, and version 2.3.1 in February 2020.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Jörg Hellmich (ELFIN GmbH) is the chairman of this SIG and manages a wiki of the CANopen lift community with content about CANopen lift.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] CAN DBC files are standardized ASCII files used to define messages sent over a CAN bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] They define the format and purpose of each type of message, including the message IDs, signal names, scaling, offsets, and data types, and provide an interoperable aid to developing CAN bus applications.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] CAN is a low-level protocol and does not support any security features intrinsically.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] There is also no encryption in standard CAN implementations, which leaves these networks open to man-in-the-middle frame interception.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] In most implementations, applications are expected to deploy their own security mechanisms; e.g., to authenticate incoming commands or the presence of certain devices on the network.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Failure to implement adequate security measures may result in various sorts of attacks if the opponent manages to insert messages on the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] While passwords exist for some safety-critical functions, such as modifying firmware, programming keys, or controlling antilock brake actuators, these systems are not implemented universally and have a limited number of seed/key pairs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] When developing or troubleshooting the CAN bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyse, decode and store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] There are also specialist tools as well as CAN bus monitors.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] A CAN bus monitor is an analysis tool, often a combination of hardware and software, used during development of hardware that uses the CAN bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Typically the CAN bus monitor will listen to the traffic on the CAN bus in order to display it in a user interface.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Often the CAN bus monitor offers the possibility to simulate CAN bus activity by sending CAN frames to the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] The CAN bus monitor can therefore be used to validate expected CAN traffic from a given device or to simulate CAN traffic in order to validate the reaction from a given device connected to the CAN bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Bosch holds patents on the technology, though those related to the original protocol have now expired.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of CAN-compatible microprocessors pay license fees to Bosch for use of the CAN trademark and any of the newer patents related to CAN FD, and these are normally passed on to the customer in the price of the chip.
[src:can-bus-automotive/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of products with custom ASICs or FPGAs containing CAN-compatible modules need to pay a fee for the CAN Protocol License if they wish to use the CAN trademark or CAN FD capabilities.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] FlexRay is a communication bus designed to ensure high data rates, fault tolerance, operating on a time cycle, split into static and dynamic segments for event-triggered and time-triggered communications.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] It is mainly used in aeronautic and automotive sectors.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] FlexRay supports data rates up to 10 Mbit/s, explicitly supports both star and bus physical topologies, and can have two independent data channels for fault-tolerance (communication can continue with reduced bandwidth if one channel is inoperative).
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The bus operates on a time cycle, divided into two parts: the static segment and the dynamic segment.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The static segment is preallocated into slices for individual communication types, providing stronger determinism than its predecessor CAN.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The dynamic segment operates more like CAN, with nodes taking control of the bus as available, allowing event-triggered behavior.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] There were also Premium Associate and Associate members of FlexRay consortium.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] By September 2009, there were 28 premium associate members and more than 60 associate members.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] At the end of 2009, the consortium disbanded.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The first series production vehicle with FlexRay was at the end of 2006 in the BMW X5 (E70), enabling a new and fast adaptive damping system.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Full use of FlexRay was introduced in 2008 in the new BMW 7 Series (F01).
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The FlexRay system consists of a bus and electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The clock drift must be not more than 0.15% from the reference clock, so the difference between the slowest and the fastest clock in the system is no greater than 0.3%.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] This means that, if ECU-s is a sender and ECU-r is a receiver, then for every 300 cycles of the sender there will be between 299 and 301 cycles of the receiver.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The clocks are resynchronized frequently enough to assure that this causes no problems.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The clock is sent in the static segment.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] At each time, only one ECU writes to the bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Each bit to be sent is held on the bus for 8 sample clock cycles.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The receiver keeps a buffer of the last 5 samples, and uses the majority of the last 5 samples as the input signal.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Single-cycle transmission errors may affect results near the boundary of the bits, but will not affect cycles in the middle of the 8-cycle region.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The value of the bit is sampled in the middle of the 8-bit region.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The errors are moved to the extreme cycles, and the clock is synchronized frequently enough for the drift to be small.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] All the communication is sent in the form of frames.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] If nothing is being communicated, the bus is held in state 1 (high voltage), so every receiver knows that the communication started when the voltage drops to 0.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] The receiver knows when the message is complete by checking whether BSS0 (1) or FES (0) was received.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Note that 8-cycle per bit has nothing to do with bytes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] 16 for BSS0 and BSS1 and 64 for its bits.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Also note that BSS0 has value 1, and BSS1 has value 0.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Clocks are resynchronized when the voted signal changes from 1 to 0, if the receiver was in either idle state or expecting BSS1.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] As synchronization is done on the voted signal, small transmission errors during synchronization that affect the boundary bits may skew the synchronization no more than 1 cycle.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] As there are at most 88 cycles between synchronization (BSS1, 8 bits of the last byte, FES and TES - 11 bits of 8 cycles each), and the clock drift is no larger than 1 per 300 cycles, the drift may skew the clock no more than 1 cycle.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Small transmission errors during the receiving may affect only the boundary bits.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] So in the worst case the two middle bits are correct, and thus the sampled value is correct.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Here's an example of a particularly bad case - error during synchronization, a lost cycle due to clock drift and error in transmission.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Despite so many errors, the communication was received correctly.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] All except the first are synchronized by the 1->0 edge in the transmission fragment shown.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] When developing and/or troubleshooting the FlexRay bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools which collect, analyze, decode, store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:can-bus-automotive/flexray] Ethernet may replace FlexRay for bandwidth intensive, non-safety critical applications.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The need for a cheap serial network arose as the technologies and the facilities implemented in the car grew, while the CAN bus was too expensive to implement for every component in the car.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] European car manufacturers started using different serial communication technologies, which led to compatibility problems.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] In the late 1990s, the LIN Consortium was founded by five automakers (BMW, Volkswagen Group, Audi, Volvo Cars, Mercedes-Benz), with the technologies supplied (networking and hardware expertise) from Volcano Automotive Group and Motorola.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The first fully implemented version of the new LIN specification (LIN version 1.3) was published in November 2002.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] In September 2003, version 2.0 was introduced to expand capabilities and make provisions for additional diagnostics features.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] LIN may be used also over the vehicle's battery power line with a special LIN-over-DC-power-line (DC-LIN) transceiver.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] LIN over DC power line (DC-LIN) was standardized as ISO/AWI 17987-8.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] CAN in Automation has been appointed by the ISO Technical Management Board (TMB) as the Registration Authority for the LIN Supplier ID standardized in the ISO 17987 series.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] LIN is a broadcast serial network comprising 16 nodes (one primary and up to 15 secondary nodes).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] All messages are initiated by the primary node with at most one secondary node replying to a given message identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The primary node can also act as a secondary node by replying to its own messages.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Because all communications are initiated by the primary node it is not necessary to implement a collision detection.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The primary and secondary nodes are typically microcontrollers, but may be implemented in specialized hardware or ASICs in order to save cost, space, or power.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Current uses combine the low-cost efficiency of LIN and simple sensors to create small networks.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] These sub-systems can be connected by a back-bone network (i.e.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The LIN bus is an inexpensive serial communications protocol, which effectively supports remote application within a car's network.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] It is particularly intended for mechatronic nodes in distributed automotive applications, but is equally suited to industrial applications.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] It is intended to complement the existing CAN network leading to hierarchical networks within cars.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] In the late 1990s the Local Interconnect Network (LIN) Consortium was founded by five European automakers, Mentor Graphics (Formerly Volcano Automotive Group) and Freescale (Formerly Motorola, now NXP).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The first fully implemented version of the new LIN specification was published in November 2002 as LIN version 1.3.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] In September 2003 version 2.0 was introduced to expand configuration capabilities and make provisions for significant additional diagnostics features and tool interfaces.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Data is transferred across the bus in fixed-form messages of selectable lengths.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The master task transmits a header that consists of a break signal followed by synchronization and identifier fields.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The slaves respond with a data frame that consists of 2, 4 or 8 data bytes plus 3 bytes of control information.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] **Event-triggered frame.** The purpose of this is to increase the responsiveness of the LIN cluster without assigning too much of the bus bandwidth to the polling of multiple slave nodes with seldom occurring events.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The first data byte of the carried unconditional frame shall be equal to a protected identifier assigned to an event-triggered frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] A slave shall reply with an associated unconditional frame only if its data value has changed.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] If none of the slave tasks responds to the header the rest of the frame slot is silent and the header is ignored.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] If more than one slave task responds to the header in the same frame slot a collision will occur, and the master has to resolve the collision by requesting all associated unconditional frames before requesting the event-triggered frame again.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] **Sporadic frame.** This frame is transmitted by the master as required, so a collision cannot occur.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The header of a sporadic frame shall only be sent in its associated frame slot when the master task knows that a signal carried in the frame has been updated.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The publisher of the sporadic frame shall always provide the response to the header.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] **Diagnostic frame.** These always carry diagnostic or configuration data and they always contain eight data bytes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The identifier is either 60 (0x3C), called master request frame, or 61(0x3D), called slave response frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Before generating the header of a diagnostic frame, the master task asks its diagnostic module if it shall be sent or if the bus shall be silent.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The slave tasks publish and subscribe to the response according to their diagnostic module.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] **User-defined frame.** These can carry any kind of information.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] **Reserved frame.** These shall not be used in a LIN 2.0 cluster.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The LIN specification was designed to allow very cheap hardware-nodes being used within a network.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] It is a low-cost, single-wire network based on ISO 9141.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] In today’s car networking topologies, microcontrollers with either UART capability or dedicated LIN hardware are used.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The microcontroller generates all needed LIN data (protocol ...) (partly) by software and is connected to the LIN network via a LIN transceiver (simply speaking, a level shifter with some add-ons).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Working as a LIN node is only part of the possible functionality.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The LIN hardware may include this transceiver and works as a pure LIN node without added functionality.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] As LIN Slave nodes should be as cheap as possible, they may generate their internal clocks by using RC oscillators instead of crystal oscillators (quartz or a ceramic).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] To ensure the baud rate-stability within one LIN frame, the SYNC field within the header is used.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The LIN-Master uses one or more predefined scheduling tables to start the sending and receiving to the LIN bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] These scheduling tables contain at least the relative timing, where the message sending is initiated.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] One LIN Frame consists of the two parts: **header** and **response**.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The header is always sent by the LIN Master, while the response is sent by either one dedicated LIN-Slave or the LIN master itself.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Transmitted data within the LIN is transmitted serially as eight bit data bytes with one start bit, one stop-bit, and no parity (break field does not have a start or stop bit).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Bit rates vary within the range of 1 kbit/s to 20 kbit/s.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Data on the bus is divided into recessive (logical HIGH) and dominant (logical LOW).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The time normally is considered by the LIN Masters stable clock source, the smallest entity is one bit time (52 μs @ 19.2 kbit/s).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Two bus states – sleep-mode and active – are used within the LIN protocol.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] While data is on the bus, all LIN-nodes are asked to be in the active state.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] After a specified timeout, the nodes enter sleep mode and will be released back to active state by a WAKEUP frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] This frame may be sent by any node requesting activity on the bus, either the LIN Master following its internal schedule, or one of the attached LIN Slaves being activated by its internal software application.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] After all nodes are awakened, the Master continues to schedule the next Identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] There is an Inter Byte Space between the BREAK and SYNC field, one between the SYNC and IDENTIFIER, one between the payload and Checksum and one between every Data byte in the payload.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] If the identifier causes one *physical* LIN slave to send the response, the identifier may be called a Rx-identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] If the *master's slave task* sends data to the bus, it may be called Tx-identifier.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The response is sent by one of the attached LIN slave **tasks** and is divided into data and checksum.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] These methods allow the detection of the position of slave nodes on the LIN bus and allow the assignment of a unique node address (NAD).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Each slave node has to provide two extra pins, one input, D1, and one output, D2.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Each configuration pin Dx (x=1-2) has additional circuitry to aid in the position detection.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] 2.1 The first non addressed SNPD node is selected.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Each slave node needs some additional circuitry compared to the standard LIN circuitry to aid in the position detection.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] At the start of the procedure, none of the SNPD devices have a NAD assigned.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] The autoaddressing routine is performed during the sync field.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] This technique is covered by the patents EP 1490772 B1 and US 7091876.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] LIN is not a full replacement of the CAN bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] But the LIN bus is a good alternative wherever low costs are essential and speed/bandwidth is not important.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Typically, it is used within sub-systems that are not critical to vehicle performance or safety - some examples are given below.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] Addressing in LIN is achieved with a NAD (Node ADdress) that is part of the PID (protected identifier).
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] NAD values are on 7bits, so in the range 1 to 127 (0x7F) and it is a composition of supplier ID, function ID and variant ID.
[src:can-bus-automotive/local-interconnect-network] You can obtain a supplier ID by contacting CAN in Automation that is the authority responsible for the assignment of such identifiers.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] SAE standard J1979 defines many OBD-II PIDs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] All on-road vehicles and trucks sold in North America are required to support a subset of these codes, primarily for state mandated emissions inspections.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Manufacturers also define additional PIDs specific to their vehicles.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Though not mandated, many motorcycles also support OBD-II PIDs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] In 1996, light duty vehicles (less than 8,500 lb or 3,900 kg) were the first to be mandated followed by medium duty vehicles (8,500–14,000 lb or 3,900–6,400 kg) in 2005.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] They are both required to be accessed through a standardized data link connector defined by SAE J1962.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Heavy duty vehicles (greater than 14,000 lb or 6,400 kg) made after 2010, for sale in the US are allowed to support OBD-II diagnostics through SAE standard J1939-13 (a round diagnostic connector) according to CARB in title 13 CCR 1971.1.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Some heavy duty trucks in North America use the SAE J1962 OBD-II diagnostic connector that is common with passenger cars, notably Mack and Volvo Trucks, however they use 29 bit CAN identifiers (unlike 11 bit headers used by passenger cars).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] There are 10 diagnostic services described in the latest OBD-II standard SAE J1979.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Before 2002, J1979 referred to these services as "modes".
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Vehicle manufacturers are not required to support all services.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each manufacturer may define additional services above #9 (e.g.: service 22 as defined by SAE J2190 for Ford/GM, service 21 for Toyota) for other information e.g. the voltage of the traction battery in a hybrid electric vehicle (HEV).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The nonOBD UDS services start at 0x10 to avoid overlap of ID-range.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The table below shows the standard OBD-II PIDs as defined by SAE J1979.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The expected response for each PID is given, along with information on how to translate the response into meaningful data.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Again, not all vehicles will support all PIDs and there can be manufacturer-defined custom PIDs that are not defined in the OBD-II standard.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Note that services 01 and 02 are basically identical, except that service 01 provides current information, whereas service 02 provides a snapshot of the same data taken at the point when the last diagnostic trouble code was set.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The exceptions are PID 01, which is only available in service 01, and PID 02, which is only available in service 02.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] If service 02 PID 02 returns zero, then there is no snapshot and all other service 02 data is meaningless.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] When using Bit-Encoded-Notation, quantities like C4 means bit 4 from data byte C.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each bit is numbered from 0 to 7, so 7 is the most significant bit and 0 is the least significant bit (See below).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Service 02 accepts the same PIDs as service 01, with the same meaning, but information given is from when the freeze frame was created.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Note that PID $02 is used to obtain the DTC that triggered the freeze frame.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A person has to send the frame number in the data section of the message.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Some of the PIDs in the above table cannot be explained with a simple formula.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 4 bytes of data (Big-endian).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each bit, from MSB to LSB, represents one of the next 32 PIDs and specifies whether that PID is supported.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 4 bytes of data, labeled A, B, C and D.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first byte (A) contains two pieces of information.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bit A7 (MSB of byte A) indicates whether or not the MIL (malfunction indicator light, aka. check engine light) is illuminated.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bits A6 through A0 represent the number of diagnostic trouble codes currently flagged in the ECU.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The second, third, and fourth bytes (B, C and D) give information about the availability and completeness of certain on-board tests ("OBD readiness checks").
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The third and fourth bytes are to be interpreted differently depending upon whether the engine is spark ignition (e.g.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Otto or Wankel engines) or compression ignition (e.g.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] In the second byte (B), bit 3 indicates the engine type and thus how to interpret bytes C and D, with 0 being spark (Otto or Wankel) and 1 (set) being compression (Diesel).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bits B6 to B4 and B2 to B0 are used for information about tests that not engine-type specific, and thus termed *common* tests.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Note that for bits indicating test **availability** a bit set to 1 indicates available, whilst for bits indicating test **completeness** a bit set to 0 indicates complete.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bytes C and D are mapped as follows for spark ignition engine types (e.g.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] NMHC *may* stand for Non-Methane HydroCarbons, but J1979 does not enlighten us.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The translation would be the ammonia sensor in the SCR catalyst.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 4 bytes of data.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The data returned is of an identical form to that returned for PID 01, with one exception - the first byte is always zero.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for one of these two PIDs will return 9 bytes of data.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] PID 78 returns data relating to EGT sensors for bank 1, whilst PID 79 similarly returns data for bank 2.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first byte is a bit encoded field indicating which EGT sensors are supported for the respective bank.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bytes B through I provide 16-bit integers indicating the temperatures of the sensors.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The temperature values are interpreted in degrees Celsius in the range -40 to 6513.5 (scale 0.1), using the usual $(A\times 256+B)/10-40$ formula (MSB is A, LSB is B).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Only values for which the corresponding sensor is supported are meaningful.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this service returns a list of the DTCs that have been set.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The list is encapsulated using the ISO 15765-2 protocol.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] If there are two or fewer DTCs (up to 4 bytes) then they are returned in an ISO-TP Single Frame (SF).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Three or more DTCs in the list are reported in multiple frames, with the exact count of frames dependent on the communication type and addressing details.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each trouble code requires 2 bytes to describe.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Encoded in these bytes are a category and a number.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] It is typically shown decoded into a five-character form like "U0158", where the first character (here 'U') represents the category the DTC belongs to, and the remaining four characters are a hexadecimal representation of the number under that category.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first two bits (A7 and A6) of the first byte (A) represent the category.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The remaining 14 bits represent the number.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Of note is that since the second character is formed from only two bits, it can thus only be within the range 0-3.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] "U0158", can be looked up in a table of OBD-II DTCs to get an actual description of what it represents.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Of note, whilst some blocks of DTC code ranges have generic meanings that apply to all vehicles and manufacturers, the meanings of others can vary per manufacturer or even model.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] It is also worth noting that DTCs may sometimes be encountered in a four-character form, e.g.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] "C158", which is simply the plain hexadecimal representation of the two bytes, with proper decoding with respect to the category not having been performed.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] It provides information about track in-use performance for catalyst banks, oxygen sensor banks, evaporative leak detection systems, EGR systems and secondary air system.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The numerator for each component or system tracks the number of times that all conditions necessary for a specific monitor to detect a malfunction have been encountered.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The denominator for each component or system tracks the number of times that the vehicle has been operated in the specified conditions.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The count of data items should be reported at the beginning (the first byte).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] All data items of the In-use Performance Tracking record consist of two bytes and are reported in this order (each message contains two items, hence the message length is 4).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] It provides information about track in-use performance for NMHC catalyst, NOx catalyst monitor, NOx adsorber monitor, PM filter monitor, exhaust gas sensor monitor, EGR/ VVT monitor, boost pressure monitor and fuel system monitor.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] Some PIDs are to be interpreted specially, and aren't necessarily exactly bitwise encoded, or in any scale.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The values for these PIDs are enumerated.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 2 bytes of data.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first byte describes fuel system #1.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The second byte describes fuel system #2 (if it exists) and is encoded identically to the first byte.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns a single byte of data which describes the secondary air status.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns a single byte of data which describes which OBD standards this ECU was designed to comply with.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] This PID returns a value from an enumerated list giving the fuel type of the vehicle.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] There are currently no definitions for flexible-fuel vehicle.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The majority of all OBD-II PIDs in use are non-standard.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] For most modern vehicles, there are many more functions supported on the OBD-II interface than are covered by the standard PIDs, and there is relatively minor overlap between vehicle manufacturers for these non-standard PIDs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] There is very limited information available in the public domain for non-standard PIDs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] The primary source of information on non-standard PIDs across different manufacturers is maintained by the US-based Equipment and Tool Institute and only available to members.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p01] However, even ETI membership will not provide full documentation for non-standard PIDs.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] As defined in ISO 15765-4, emissions protocols (including OBD-II, EOBD, UDS, etc.) use the ISO-TP transport layer (ISO 15765-2).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] All CAN frames sent using ISO-TP use a data length of 8 bytes (and DLC of 8).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] It is recommended to pad the unused data bytes with 0xCC.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] The PID query and response occurs on the vehicle's CAN bus.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] Standard OBD requests and responses use functional addresses.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] The diagnostic reader initiates a query using CAN ID 7DFh, which acts as a broadcast address, and accepts responses from any ID in the range 7E8h to 7EFh.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] ECUs that can respond to OBD queries listen both to the functional broadcast ID of 7DFh and one assigned ID in the range 7E0h to 7E7h.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] Their response has an ID of their assigned ID plus 8 e.g.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] This approach allows up to eight ECUs, each independently responding to OBD queries.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] The diagnostic reader can use the ID in the ECU response frame to continue communication with a specific ECU.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] In particular, multi-frame communication requires a response to the specific ECU ID rather than to ID 7DFh.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] CAN bus may also be used for communication beyond the standard OBD messages.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] Physical addressing uses particular CAN IDs for specific modules (e.g., 720h for the instrument cluster in Fords) with proprietary frame payloads.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] The functional PID query is sent to the vehicle on the CAN bus at ID 7DFh, using 8 data bytes.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] The vehicle responds to the PID query on the CAN bus with message IDs that depend on which module responded.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] Typically the engine or main ECU responds at ID 7E8h.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] Other modules, like the hybrid controller or battery controller in a Prius, respond at 07E9h, 07EAh, 07EBh, etc.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] These are 8h higher than the physical address the module responds to.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] Even though the number of bytes in the returned value is variable, the message uses 8 data bytes regardless (CAN bus protocol form Frameformat with 8 data bytes).
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] Same as query, except that 40h is added to the service value.
[src:can-bus-automotive/obd-ii-pids-p02] 7Fh this a general response usually indicating the module doesn't recognize the request.
